e is either the parser crashes on malformed input or the skip counter is not incremented correctly. Both are logic errors in error handling that a unit test can catch by injecting malformed entries and verifying the counter. This doesn't require a real pipeline or streaming context; the parser logic is the failure boundary.","test_description":"Create a list of log entries where 90% are valid JSON and 10% are intentionally malformed (missing closing brace, invalid escapes, non-string keys, etc.). Pass through the parser. Verify all 90% of valid entries are processed, the skip counter reports exactly 10%, and no uncaught exceptions are raised.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"The test exercises error handling in the parser with controlled inputs. Small risk that the real failure is in pipeline integration (async exception handling), but primary failure is in parser logic.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.7,"Integration":0.28,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The tool handles a burst of 10,000 log entries per second without dropping entries or falling behind.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The real failure is a performance or reliability issue under load: unbounded memory growth, single-threaded bottleneck, buffer overflow, or crashes. A unit test processes synchronously and won't reveal these. An Integration-level load test with in-memory data and simulated burst (rapid in-process feeding) can catch buffer overflows, memory pressure, and concurrency issues. System-level testing with real I/O might reveal additional bottlenecks, but the stated behavior is testable at Integration.","test_description":"Create 10,000 log entries in memory and feed them to the tool as rapidly as possible (e.g., in a tight loop, simulating 10,000 entries/sec burst). Measure processing time. Verify (a) output contains all 10,000 entries with no data loss, (b) processing completes in reasonable time (<2 seconds), (c) tool does not crash, hang, or exhaust memory. Include malformed entries in the burst to test robustness under load.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"The test exercises performance and resilience under burst load in-process. A true System test with real I/O might reveal additional failures, but Integration-level load testing adequately covers the stated behavior.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.28,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0.02}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13591,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13591},"output_tokens":4,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"60d37389-2ecf-4198-be8e-30768750d71f","uuid":"594b7737-31a3-40f2-82eb-24ffc5d1cd8a"}
